+
+## 15. Core acceptance cases
+
+### UAT-R01 — Sparse imported contact
+
+Given a phone-imported person containing only name and phone, Liaison shows a sparse-profile review reason without marking the relationship weak. The user may assign a group, mark unknown fields, or dismiss the review.
+
+### UAT-R02 — Close low-frequency friend
+
+Given a core friend with a yearly cadence and a meaningful interaction six months ago, Liaison does not flag the relationship overdue merely because another user’s default monthly cadence exists.
+
+### UAT-R03 — Explainable priority
+
+Given a person with an overdue cadence, birthday in ten days, and one open promise, the review card lists each component, formula version, and contribution. Changing the birthday weight updates the preview before saving.
+
+### UAT-R04 — No universal completeness pressure
+
+Given a friend with no travel pack enabled, the missing seat preference does not reduce general profile readiness or raise review priority.
+
+### UAT-R05 — Group and company filtering
+
+Given people with multiple dated organization memberships, a query for current Dublin employees at Acme returns only active Dublin memberships and preserves historical roles for as-of queries.
+
+### UAT-R06 — Connected calendar and file
+
+Given a calendar invitation and local briefing file linked to a person, both appear in the person timeline and resource tab. Removing the calendar connector preserves the local link and provenance without deleting the briefing.
+
+### UAT-R07 — Neurodivergent low-capacity day
+
+Given a user who selects low social capacity, the daily review shows no more than the configured number, explains the choices, and permits snoozing the whole queue without creating a red overdue backlog.
+
+### UAT-R08 — Private relationship assessment
+
+Given a private trust/closeness snapshot in an EA overlay, another workspace member and subject-facing export cannot retrieve or infer it through search, graph, API, MCP, export, or counts.
+
+### UAT-R09 — Monthly review
+
+Given a month of interactions, Liaison produces a Markdown review showing contacted people, cadence mismatches, sparse profiles, open commitments, upcoming dates, and decisions. The review records the policy version used.
+
+### UAT-R10 — Manual archive
+
+Given an inactive relationship, archiving records reason and date, suppresses maintenance prompts, preserves history, and permits later restoration without changing the stable entity ID.
+
+---
+
+## 16. Recommended release sequence
+
+### Slice 1 — Relationship memory core
+
+- people;
+- organizations;
+- groups;
+- relationships;
+- notes;
+- interactions;
+- reminders;
+- important dates;
+- static fields and Markdown profiles;
+- quick capture;
+- basic search/filter.
+
+### Slice 2 — Review and attention
+
+- relationship intent;
+- cadence;
+- reason-only queue;
+- monthly review;
+- open commitments;
+- sparse/stale profile views;
+- no-guilt capacity controls.
+
+### Slice 3 — Topic Packs and context readiness
+
+- built-in packs;
+- custom fields;
+- field states and provenance;
+- context-specific readiness;
+- profile layout editor;
+- saved views.
+
+### Slice 4 — Resources, organizations, and graph
+
+- local files and URLs;
+- calendar references;
+- company and membership history;
+- dynamic groups;
+- accessible graph/table parity.
+
+### Slice 5 — Weighted policies and plugins
+
+- weighted Review Priority;
+- formula editor and simulation;
+- plugin-supplied Topic Packs;
+- imported policy templates;
+- conformance tests.
+
+The weighted engine should not precede the reason-only review experience. Users must first be able to understand and trust why Liaison surfaces a person.
